default3. Questions
default&#xa0;
default3.1
default 
defaultTerrence Higgins Trust firmly disagrees with th
defaulte proposal to remove legal aid from prisoners. 
defaultThe treatment of prisoners should be given the same recourse to legal aid and justice as any other citizen
default. Removing access to le
defaultgal aid and independent review will place individuals at high risk of neglect, potentially reverting precedence through case law in recent years. 
default&#xa0;
default3.3 
defaultCurrent cases often reach court following an attempt to resolve the issue through the prison complaints
default system. If the prison complaints system is unable to resolve a problem there must still be access to the judicial system. Prisoners with HIV, blood borne viruses, STIs or any other health issue need to have access to legal advice and support to ensure tha
defaultt any mistreatment is raised and dealt with appropriately. 
defaultEqually provision of access to safer sex materials is an ongoing issue in prisons and in a recent response to the Commission on Sex in Prison we have evidence
defaultd
default the continuing problems in prison wit
defaulth limited access to safer sex materials. 
default&#xa0;
default3.4 
defaultCases of prisoners requiring legal advice for health related matters are low in number but nonetheless must have recourse to legal aid. 
defaultWe do not believe that an internal prisons complaints system will have 
defaultth
defaulte robust independent structure that the legal system has and 
defaulti
defaultnstitutions such as prisons should not be excluded from 
defaultthe checks and balances that the legal system provides. 
defaultIn addition, as prison healthcare is provided by NHS England it would not be appro
defaultpriate for matters to be 
defaultdealt with internally within the prison system when an external organisation is responsible. 
defaultThe NHS should not be
default 
defaultexcluded from the law by 
defaultvirtue
default of the setting
default in which the service is provided
default. 
defaultThe example below explains the 
defaultimportance of legal aid for prisoners and the link with the health care services.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultSam was a long term prisoner in a high security prison. 
defaultC
defaultondoms were in theory accessible on all other wings if prisoners were prepared to line up and ask f
defaultor one at a time
default from the nurse. However,
default Sam’s wing was separately medically managed from the rest of the prison, by the local Mental Health Trust. Their senior nurse decided that patients on that wing would not be supplied with condoms because he would not condone sexua
defaultl conduct between what he saw as “vulnerable” prisoners. THT’s arguments that unprotected sexual activity was already happening and in itself leaving people vulnerable to HIV and other STIs did not work until Sam used legal aid to bring a case against the 
defaultprison. Without legal aid, condoms would not have been made available to all prisoners and they would continue to be at risk of poor sexual health and life-threatening diseases.
