default&#xa0;
default4) Introducing a residence test
default4.
default1 
defaultTerrence Higgins Trust strongly 
defaultdisagrees with the proposals to introduce a residence test. Legal Aid is a valuable resource for people in the UK to be able challenge the state and defend their rights. This
default residency test wou
defaultl
defaultd
default isolate vulnerab
defaultle individuals with 
defaulta 
defaultvalid need to access t
defaulthe judicial system.
default For example, individuals who have been refused permanent leave to remain who have a health condition such as HIV and who would wish to challenge the decision on the basis of their ongoing health and wellbeing would no longer be
default able to 
defaultaccess legal aid.
default4.2 
defaultThe needs of asylum seekers should not be 
defaultoverlooked;
default whilst it is an improvement to apply the residency test from the date the asylum application is submitted it is still too restrictive and only applies to successful applicants. Given asylum seekers are normally unable to work it would not be representativ
defaulte of a fair society if they were unable to defend themselves with the relevant legal expertise. It is important to provide legal support 
defaultto people when they need it. 
defaultIndividuals establishing a new life should have the same access to
default fair and equal judgment
default with
default legal support as any other resident in the UK
default. I
defaultt is entirely unacceptable to provide Legal Aid to someone who has not lived in the UK for decades and to ignore the needs of someone living in the UK and contributing to society.  
default4.3 
defaultA
defaultnyone 
defaultgiven 
defaultper
defaultmission to rem
defaultain for a specific time period, for example
default until they turn
default18
default,
default would not be able to seek the right to remain permanently as they have not been a reside
defaultnt for 12 months based on the specifications and requirements of the proposed structure. An
defaulty child living with HIV who has built a life in the UK should be able to access the support that they need to challenge decisions about their ongoing residency. 
default4.4 
defaultFrom a practical perspective placing the responsibility on the solicitor to establish an i
defaultndividual’s resid
defaultency status is also problematic. Proving legal status is often a complex issue and will require specific expertise and additional time and resource. There is a great risk that individuals could be incorrectly prohibited from legal aid if t
defaulthe provider is unable to gain proof. 
default4.5 
defaultIndividuals will not always have relevant paperwork and there is a risk that discrimination of individuals due to government bodies and agencies mistakes or failure to provide paperwork. There will also be situatio
defaultns where vulnerable individuals may have had to leave their residence without being able to find papers and evidence of their residency status. 
