default 
default5.2 
defaultAn example of specialist knowledge would be in a case prosecuting against an individual for the transmission of 
defaultHIV. These cases are rare and 
defaultcomplex;
default they require expert knowledge and understanding of previous cases. 
defaultThere are very few legal aid providers
default with this expertise and access to them should be available across the country. It is essential that there are not geographical limitations. 
defaultProviding an ind
defaultividual with a
default local legal aid provider would risk a miscarriage of justice. An alternative system 
defaultallowing legal aid providers to register particular expertise at a local and national level would enable individuals to access the most qualified representative. 
default5.3 
defaultIt is unreasonable to expect solicitors to be ex
defaultperts in all areas of law. 
defaultThe proposals 
defaultrisk wasting public funds if a case is not comprehensively made by the most appropriate solicitor
default,
default with expert knowledge. 
defaultThe proposed approach risks poor representation
default of
default cases and an unjust use of the legal system and its practitioners. 
default5.4 
defaultT
defaulthere is
default also
default the added risk that individuals will choose to represent themselves. This is highly likely if they do not have confidence in their assigned solicitor’s ability or trust them. For any person living with HIV disclosure is difficult and for this to happ
defaulten there needs to be a relationship of trust. If an individual’s HIV status is relevant to the case and they do not trust or have confidence in the legal aid provider this will severely jeopardise their case in court. 
default5.5 
defaultThese proposals risk 
defaultcre
defaultating
default a t
defaultwo tiered legal system preventing some of the most vulnerable members
default of society to achieve justice.
default&#xa0;
defaultDavid worked for a major supermarket chain and had done for several years. When he was diagnosed with HIV he was told he needed to go onto treatment immed
defaultiately. He disclosed to his line manager, who gave him three months “gardening leave” to get used to the treatments and his diagnosis. However, at the end of the 3 months, his employer told him not to return as senior managers had decided that his HIV migh
defaultt deter customers from shopping there, were it publicly known. They went so far as to put this in writing. Despite this being an obvious breach of equality law, the employer fought the case all the way to the day of the tribunal and only settled with David
default that morning. Without legal aid, David would have been unable to pursue the case and without good legal advice he would 
defaultnot have known that the employer was likely to cave on the morning of the trial, having only held out that long in hopes that David wou
defaultld fear the publicity of a tribunal appearance more than they would.
default&#xa0;
default5
default.
default6
default To allocate cases according 
defaultto an arbitrary process will not provide a robust and credible legal aid system. With certain cases such as the criminalisation of HIV transmission it requires a particular set of expertise. The cases are incredibly rare and it would be far more credible t
defaulto allocate them on a case by case basis to the most qualified and experienced provider, regardless of location. 
default&#xa0;
default5.7
default 
defaultCase allocation should be a combination of provider expertise and client choice. Anything less would risk resulting in cases breaking down
default and miscarriages of justice and grave consequences. One such example is explained below.
default 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultTHT was contacted by a man with HIV who, on the advice of his generalist criminal law defender, had pleaded guilty to reckless GBH by sexual transmission. On reviewing the case, it was immediately obvious to us that the requirement for scientific proof of 
defaulttransmission had not been met to the agreed standard. It transpired that his defence had simply asked the prosecution whether the CPS medical report was proof of transmission and they had asserted that it was (when in fact it was not, and has repeatedly be
defaulten shown in other cases to be insufficient). 
default&#xa0;
defaultAlthough we contacted a specialist lawyer who was willing to represent him in a request to change his plea, the judge refused leave, resulting in the defendant fleeing the country and being sentenced in absent
defaultia. The defendant later died as a result of lack of access to specialist treatment while on the run. THT also knows of at least two other cases where a defendant was allowed to belatedly change their plea after they were initially gravely misadvised by a g
defaulteneralist criminal solicitor provided by the police.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default6
default.
default Paying for permission work in judicial review cases
default. 
defaultDo you agree with the proposal that providers should only be paid for work carried out on an application for judicial review, including a request for reconsideration of the application at a hearing, the renewal hearing, or an onward permission appeal to th
defaulte Court of Appeal, if permission is granted by the Court (but that reasonable disbursements should be payable in any event)? Please give reasons. 
default6
default.1 
defaultThis proposal will inevitably prompt cautious behaviour and in turn prevent applications for judicial reviews. 
defaultIt is essential that all individuals, groups and public bodies are equal before the law and answerable to it. 
defaultGovernment bodies and agencies shou
defaultld be held accountable to the law and 
defaultforced 
defaultto review decisions where
default illogical decisions have been made
default; 
defaultthese proposals
default will stop thi
defaults from happening. 
default6
default.2 
defaultWithout 
defaultguaranteed 
defaultaccess to legal aid for judicial review it will result in reduced access only 
defaultfor individuals or organisations prepared to take a risk and pay for the cost 
defaulto
defaultf judicial review application is granted. Access to justice should not be based on the ability to pay. Such a system would ostracise the vulnerable in society and result in furt
defaulther neglect.
default 
default7
default.
default Civil merits test – removing legal aid for borderline cases 
default7
default.
default1 
defaultIt is not always clear from the outset what the prospects of a case are and there are examples where whilst the prospects might be low or borderline the public interest and 
defaultconsequence is of high importan
defaultce. To ignore these cases based 
defaulton an initial judgement that they are not likely to succeed is
default 
defaultunacceptable. 
defaultThis is particularly the case of those which just miss the 50 per cent cut off. 
default&#xa0;
default7
default.2 There is a lack of clarity on 
defaulthow the likely success of a case will be decided. 
defaultAdditional evidence often comes to light
default through questioning that changes the expected outcome. Making a decision regarding funding prior to a hearing will inevitably prevent some individuals from achieving
default justice simply because they appeared unlikely to succeed.
